      <title>Why We Should Pay What Water Is Worth</title>
      <category domain="https://www.newsdeeply.com/water/economics/">Economics</category>
      <category domain="https://www.newsdeeply.com/water/management-supply/">Management &amp; Supply</category>
      <pubDate>Mon, 21 Mar 2016 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <author>Isabelle Groc</author>
      <link>https://www.newsdeeply.com/water/articles/2016/03/21/why-we-should-pay-what-water-is-worth</link>
      <guid>https://www.newsdeeply.com/water/articles/2016/03/21/why-we-should-pay-what-water-is-worth</guid>
      <description>It’s time to change the way urban customers pay for water. One way to do that is to divide bills into two parts. One part would cover the cost of providing the water and the other would be a value assigned based on the scarcity of water at that time, which would incentivize conservation.</description>
